WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.960
We need to know that the things we're producing are safe, are actually giving us the effect

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:16.680
that we are intending to create, as well as not causing any harm.

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:22.100
I think there's a lot of hope and promise to having standardized tools that are used

00:00:22.100 --> 00:00:23.100
across Pharma.

00:00:23.100 --> 00:00:26.639
The Open Source mindset allows you to ask all kinds of possibilities.

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:29.879
You can go right back and if you're not sure if something's right, you can go and explore

00:00:29.959 --> 00:00:35.759
I think there's a lot of value in Open Source because that pipeline, although somewhat idiosyncratic

00:00:35.759 --> 00:00:40.560
and unique across different Pharma companies, at the end of the day is standardized.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:45.160
You can get people who have both industry experience, they understand what it is to

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:50.160
build an Atom dataset, they understand that process, and so they have the right skills,

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:52.439
they're just a lot more transferable.

00:00:52.439 --> 00:00:57.759
So I use Posit packages almost every day when I'm working, and it makes it just incredibly

00:00:57.759 --> 00:01:02.240
easy to build a package that is quality, that it's tested.

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:06.120
As a statistician, for instance, being able to have an Open Source package that's already

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:11.160
available greatly increases how quickly you can try that method out.

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:14.239
Our submission process is still based around essentially paper submissions.

00:01:14.239 --> 00:01:19.320
We've made the paper into PDFs, but it's pretty much the same as it was 20 or 30 years ago.

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:24.040
By submitting to regulators with Open Source software, they can immediately access that

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:28.720
same code, they can run it on their own machines and verify that they are getting the same

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:30.199
results that we are.

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:36.800
We give them a lot of code in order to show, like, this is all of the things we did, and

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:42.639
when it's in an R package, it's lovely, it's easy, it's portable, it's Open Source, we

00:01:42.639 --> 00:01:45.360
don't even have to port it anywhere, it's already out there.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:49.680
I think the possibility now with Open Source, and particularly something like R, where you've

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:54.839
got a tool like Shiny, is you can start to deliver that submission in a different way.

00:01:54.839 --> 00:02:00.599
I think we'll be sharing the data directly with the regulators in the future, we'll be

00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:05.080
worried less about how we format that and get it to look really nice on a piece of paper,

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:10.000
and I hope that we'll be able to deliver these kind of interactive apps to regulators in

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:10.520
the future.

